05161nam a22006855i 9781501769405DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017694057 a10.1515/97815017694052doi  a(DE-B1597)635193  a(OCoLC)1351567067  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPG2986b.E447 2023 7aLIT0042402bisacsh04a891.7092231 aEmery, Jacob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Vortex That Unites Us :bVersions of Totality in Russian Literature /cJacob Emery. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNIU Series in Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Totalities of Russian Literature -- t1. Versions of Possession: Ghost, Demon, Idea, Discourse -- t2. The Epidemic: The Infectious Imagination of Leo Tolstoy -- t3. The Panorama: World Literature and Universal Language -- t4. The Orchestra: Dictation and Dictatorship -- t5. The Market: Humbert Humbert as Mad Man -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Vortex That Unites Us is a study of totality in Russian literature, from the foundation of the modern Russian state to the present day. Considering a diversity of texts that have in common chiefly their prominence in the Russian literary canon, Jacob Emery examines the persistent ambition in Russian literature to gather the whole world into an artwork. Emery reveals how the diversity of totalizing figures in the Russian canon—often in alliance with ideologies like the totalitarian state or enlightenment reason—strive for the frontiers of space and time in order to guarantee the coherence of the globe and the continuity of history. He expores subjects like romantic metaphors of supernatural possession; Tolstoy's conception of art as a vector of emotional contagion; the panoramic ambitions of the avant-garde to grasp the globe in a new poetic medium; efforts of Soviet utopians to harmonize the whole of social life along aesthetic lines; Mandelstam's evocation of writing as a transcendental authority that guarantees a grandiose historical rhythm even when manifested as authoritarian repression; and the mass market of cultural commodities in which the exiled Vladimir Nabokov found success with his novel Lolita. The Vortex That Unites Us reveals a common thread in the disparate works it explores, bringing into a single horizon a variety of typically siloed texts and aesthetic approaches. In all these cases, the medium of totality is the body, inspired by artistic vision and compelled by aesthetic response.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIdeology in literature. 0aRussian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aRussian literaturexThemes, motives. 0aWhole and parts (Philosophy) in literature. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aRussian totalitarianism, aesthetic and artistic totality, Russian avant-garde, universal language, Nabokov, Russian literature, Tolstoy, Dostoevsky, Lolita.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z9783111318264oZDB-23-D